1.10	Good_Behavior_Game	Good Behavior Game	The "Good Behavior Game" was first used in 1967 in Baldwin, Kansas by Muriel Saunders who was new teacher in a forth-grade classroom. Muriel Saunders, Harriet Barrish (a graduate student at the University of Kansas), and the professor and co-founder of applied-behavior analysis, the late Montrose Wolfe co-created the Good Behavior Game. In 1969. the published the immediate results of the Good Behavior Game, and that published study can be read at PUBMED.GOV. Today, this study is among the most cited behavior change studies in the world. In 2009, the Institute of Medicine Report on the Prevention of Mental, Emotional and Behavioral Disorders as one of the most powerful prevention strategies that classroom teachers can use.	
